<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="growth-linkedin-strategy">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>marketing</group>
    <domain>smm-manager</domain>
    <summary>Build B2B authority on LinkedIn with a four-stage cycle: optimize profile, create resonant content, engage daily, and convert to business. Post 3-5x/week and comment 20+ posts daily.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>linkedin</tag>
      <tag>growth</tag>
      <tag>b2b</tag>
      <tag>content</tag>
      <tag>engagement</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>LinkedIn Growth Strategy</title>

    <summary>A systematic playbook for building B2B authority and generating inbound leads on LinkedIn. The four-stage cycle is: Optimize profile as a landing page → Create resonant content (personal stories, contrarian takes, how-to posts, carousels) → Engage via substantive daily commenting → Convert attention to business through lead magnets and DM sequences. Core rule: post 3-5 times per week and comment on 20+ posts daily — organic reach compounds only with consistent engagement.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>LinkedIn's organic reach remains higher than any other B2B platform, but it rewards personal voice and authentic narratives, not corporate announcements. The algorithm surfaces posts with early engagement in the first hour; commenting strategy on high-follower posts drives profile discovery at lower cost than standalone posts. Profile optimization converts arriving visitors — a weak headline wastes the traffic that content generates.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Building thought leadership and inbound pipeline for a B2B product or consultancy</item>
        <item>Launching a personal brand for a founder, consultant, or specialist</item>
        <item>Generating a 4-week content calendar with post types and schedule</item>
        <item>Auditing and rewriting a LinkedIn profile for conversion</item>
        <item>Analyzing engagement data from Shield or LinkedIn Analytics exports</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Real-time engagement (commenting, replying) — requires human authenticity; automated comments are detectable and harm credibility</item>
        <item>LinkedIn Sales Navigator automation — violates LinkedIn ToS; accounts get banned</item>
        <item>Accounts with no defined content pillars or brand context — generic posts perform below average</item>
        <item>Replacing human relationship-building in DMs — drafts can be prepared but must be sent and adapted by a human</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="profile-as-landing-page">
      <p>Content drives traffic; the profile converts it. A weak headline wastes all the impressions that posts generate — visitors arrive, see no clear value, and leave without following.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Treat the LinkedIn profile as a landing page: every element (headline, photo, banner, About, Featured, Experience) must reinforce a single value proposition.</statement>
        <rationale>Content drives traffic; the profile converts it. A weak headline wastes all the impressions that posts generate — visitors arrive, see no clear value, and leave without following.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Write headlines using the formula: [What you do] | [For whom] | [Proof or differentiator] — not just a job title.</statement>
        <rationale>Job titles describe employment; headlines must answer "what's in it for me?" for the visitor. Proof elements (numbers, exits, brands) signal credibility before the visitor reads further.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Strong LinkedIn headlines">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Helping SaaS founders hit $1M ARR | 3x exits | DM me 'growth'
Building AI tools for marketers | CEO @ProductName | ex-Google
Writing about product strategy | 50K newsletter | Author of [Book]]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="Weak LinkedIn headlines">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Co-founder at XYZ
Software Engineer | Python | JavaScript]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="content-types">
      <rule>
        <statement>Anchor content to personal stories, contrarian takes, and how-to posts — not company announcements or generic industry news.</statement>
        <rationale>LinkedIn's algorithm surfaces posts with early engagement. Personal and opinionated content generates comments in the first hour; announcements and news do not. Organic reach for personal-voice posts is 3-5x higher than corporate-voice posts.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Personal stories: vulnerability + concrete lesson from experience</item>
        <item>Contrarian takes: challenge a common belief with evidence</item>
        <item>How-to posts: numbered steps with one actionable takeaway each</item>
        <item>Lessons learned: "After N years in X, here's what I know"</item>
        <item>Carousels: visual guides with one point per slide (highest save rate)</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="post-structure">
      <rule>
        <statement>Write the first line of every post as if it is the only line the reader will see — LinkedIn truncates after 2-3 lines; the hook must earn the "see more" click.</statement>
        <rationale>80% of LinkedIn feed readers never click "see more." If the first line does not create a question or tension, the post receives no engagement from that 80%.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Do not put URLs in the body of LinkedIn posts — put them in the first comment.</statement>
        <rationale>LinkedIn's algorithm suppresses posts with external links in the body, reducing organic reach by 40-60%.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Hook: attention-grabbing first line</item>
        <item>Gap: blank line for readability</item>
        <item>Story/Context: 2-3 short paragraphs</item>
        <item>Value/Lesson: the insight or actionable takeaway</item>
        <item>CTA: a question or simple call to action</item>
      </list>

      <reference path="templates/story-post.txt">Story post template with hook-gap-lesson-CTA structure</reference>
      <reference path="templates/how-to-post.txt">How-to post template</reference>
      <reference path="templates/carousel-structure.txt">10-slide carousel outline</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="posting-schedule">
      <rule>
        <statement>Post 3-5 text posts per week and 1-2 carousels per week; comment on 20+ posts daily — the commenting compounds faster than standalone posts for early-stage accounts.</statement>
        <rationale>Comments on high-follower posts (50K+) drive more profile visits than an equivalent standalone post, because the comment is seen by the original poster's entire audience.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Best days: Tuesday through Thursday</item>
        <item>Best times: 7-8 AM, 12 PM, 5-6 PM in audience timezone</item>
        <item>Avoid: weekends for B2B content</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="comment-strategy">
      <rule>
        <statement>Comment with substantive additions — a specific reaction, your experience or counter-data, and a question — never with "Great post!" or emoji-only responses.</statement>
        <rationale>Substantive comments are indexed by LinkedIn and seen by the original poster's followers. Emoji-only comments are ignored by the algorithm and signal low-quality engagement to observers.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Substantive comment">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[This resonates. I tried X approach last year and found Y worked better for our audience. Have you tested that variation?]]></code>
      </example>

      <rule>
        <statement>Comment early (within the first hour) on posts from key people in your niche — early engagement receives disproportionate algorithm amplification.</statement>
        <rationale>LinkedIn's algorithm amplifies posts with rapid early engagement. Being among the first 5-10 commenters puts your comment at the top of the thread and in front of the poster's entire audience.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="connection-and-conversion-strategy">
      <rule>
        <statement>Personalize every connection request with a specific observation about the recipient's work — generic requests have a 20-30% acceptance rate vs 50%+ for personalized ones.</statement>
        <rationale>Personalization signals that you have actually looked at the profile, which differentiates from the mass-connection pattern that most people recognize and reject.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Follow up new connections with a value-first DM, not a pitch — the first DM must give something (resource, insight, genuine compliment) before asking for anything.</statement>
        <rationale>Pitching in the first DM is the single most common LinkedIn mistake; it triggers immediate disconnection and harms your reputation with that person.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="DM welcome template for new connections">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Hey [Name], thanks for connecting!

I noticed you're [something specific from their profile].

I share [content type] about [topic] here — hope you find it useful.

If you ever want to chat about [topic], always happy to connect.

[Your Name]]]></code>
      </example>

      <rule>
        <statement>Enable Creator Mode before any growth push — it adds a follower button and newsletter CTA that standard profiles lack.</statement>
        <rationale>Creator Mode changes the primary action button from "Connect" to "Follow," which has lower friction for new visitors and directly grows your addressable audience.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Lead magnets: link to a free resource in the Featured section</item>
        <item>Newsletter: CTA at end of every post drives subscribers</item>
        <item>Content mentions: natural product references inside valuable content</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="metrics">
      <rule>
        <statement>Track engagement rate (target 3%, great 7%+) and profile views per week (target 200, great 1K+) as the primary health signals — follower count is a lagging indicator.</statement>
        <rationale>Follower count grows slowly and can be inflated by low-quality connections. Engagement rate and profile views indicate whether content and profile are converting attention into interest.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Post impressions: good 5K, great 20K+</item>
        <item>Engagement rate: good 3%, great 7%+</item>
        <item>Profile views per week: good 200, great 1K+</item>
        <item>Connection accept rate: good 30%, great 50%+</item>
      </list>

      <reference path="templates/top-posts-analyzer.py">Parse Shield analytics CSV to find top posts by engagement rate</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Posting corporate speak or company announcements as personal content.</description>
        <reason>Nobody follows a person to read press releases. LinkedIn rewards personal voice; corporate voice produces near-zero organic reach.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Posting inconsistently — 3 posts one week, nothing for 2 weeks.</description>
        <reason>LinkedIn's algorithm weights recency and consistency. Gaps reset your distribution baseline and require rebuilding momentum from scratch.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/story-post.txt" purpose="Story post structure: hook, gap, lesson sequence, CTA"/>
      <template path="templates/how-to-post.txt" purpose="Step-by-step how-to post template with CTA"/>
      <template path="templates/carousel-structure.txt" purpose="10-slide carousel outline: Hook / Promise / Value slides / Summary / CTA"/>
      <template path="templates/top-posts-analyzer.py" purpose="Parse Shield analytics CSV to find top posts by engagement rate"/>
    </templates>

